@node ROM files, Keymap files, System files, System files
@section ROM files

Every emulator requires its own ROM set.  For the VIC20 and the C64, the
ROM set consists in the following files:

@itemize @bullet

@item
@file{kernal},  the Kernal ROM (8 KBytes)

@item
@file{basic}, the Basic ROM (8 KBytes)

@item
@file{chargen}, the character generator ROM (4 Kbytes)

@item
@file{dos1541}, the 1541 drive ROM (16 Kbytes)

@end itemize

The C128 needs the following files instead:

@itemize @bullet

@item
@file{kernal}, the Kernal ROM (8 Kbytes)

@item
@file{basic}, the BASIC + Editor ROM (32 Kbytes)

@item
@file{chargen}, the character generator ROM (4 Kbytes)

@item
@file{dos1541}, the 1541 drive ROM (16 Kbytes)

@end itemize

The PET emulator uses a quite different setup instead: the Basic and
Kernal ROMS are packed into a single file and only three kernal files
are provided; one for each basic revision.  To handle the different
screen sizes and keyboards, different so-called ``editor-ROMs'' for the
memory range $E000-$E800 are provided.  The kernal files contain an
editor ROM for 40 columns and graphics keyboard already.  The PET ROMs
have the following names:

@itemize @bullet

@item
@file{pet2001}, the PET2001 Basic 1 + Kernal ROM (16 KBytes)

@item
@file{pet3032}, the PET3032 Basic 2 + Kernal ROM (16 KBytes)

@item
@file{pet4032}, the PET4032/8032 Basic 4 + Kernal ROM (20
KBytes)

@item
@file{edit2.b}, the PET3032 editor for business keyboard (2
KBytes)

@item
@file{edit4.b40}, the PET4032 editor for business keyboard
(2 KBytes)

@item
@file{edit4.b80}, the PET8032 editor for 80 columns and
business keyboard (2 KBytes)

@end itemize

The PETs also have sockets for extension ROMs for the addresses
$9000-$9FFF, $A000-$AFFF and $B000-$BFFF (the last one for PET2001 and
PET3032 only).  You can specify ROM image files for those extensions
command line options @code{-petrom9}, @code{-petromA} and
@code{-petromB} resp.

An alternative would be to specify a long kernal ROM with the -kernal
option that includes the extension ROM areas already.

Also, you can specify a replacement for the basic ROM at $B000-$DFFF
with the @code{-petromBasic} option and a replacement for the editor ROM
at $E000-$E7FF with the @code{-petromEditor} option.

You can also edit the configuration file as explained in the
appropriate section.
