@node Sending feedback, Contributing, Homepage, Contacts
@section How to send feedback

If you want to report bugs, make suggestions or contribute to
the project, please email one of the following people:

@itemize @bullet

@item
Teemu Rantanen (@email{tvr@@cs.hut.fi}) for the SID stuff;

@item
Andreas Boose (@email{boose@@unixserv.rz.fh-hannover.de}) for the 1541
disk drive;

@item
Andr@'e Fachat (@email{fachat@@physik.tu-chemnitz.de}) for the PETs;

@item
Ettore Perazzoli (@email{ettore@@comm2000.it}), the current
maintainer, for everything else.

@end itemize

It's always nice to receive feedback and/or bugreports about VICE, but
please read these few notes before sending mail to anybody in the
team.

@itemize @bullet

@item
Please put the word @samp{VICE} @emph{in all capitals} in your subject
line (e.g. @samp{VICE fails to run game XXX}).  This helps mail
splitting and reduces chances that your message is unintentionally
deleted, forgotten or lost.

@item
Please don't send any HTML mail (we really hate that!).  If you use
M$ Outlook or Netscape Communicator, make sure you turn off the
"rich text" (HTML) feature.

@item
Please don't send @emph{any} binaries without asking first.

@item
Please read the following documents carefully before reporting a bug
or a problem you cannot solve:

@itemize @bullet
@item
the VICE documentation (you are reading it!);
@item
the VICE FAQ (it is available on the Internet, and reachable from the
VICE home page:
@uref{http://www.tu-chemnitz.de/~fachat/vice/vice.html});
@item
the comp.emulators.cbm and comp.sys.cbm FAQs (@pxref{FAQs you should
read}).
@end itemize

@item
When you report a bug, please try to be as accurate as possible and
describe how it can be reproduced to the very detail.  You should also
tell us what machine you are running on, what operating system you are
using as well as the version of it.

@item
Please don't ask us how to transfer original C64 disk or tapes to your
PC; this has been asked a gazillion times through email.  To transfer
disks, you can use the Star Commander
(@uref{http://ludens.elte.hu/~sta/sc.html}).  And no, you cannot read
C64 disks with your old 5"1/4 PC drive.  To transfer tapes, we have been
told a tool is in the works.  If you are impatient, you'll have to write
your own tool (and of course make it available as @emph{free} software
with open sources, so that other people can enjoy it as much as you do).

@item
Please don't ask us where to find games for the emulator on the
Internet.

@item
Please don't ask us when the next version will be out, because we
really don't know.

@item
Please write in English, or in the language of the person you
are writing to (Ettore is Italian, Andr@'e and Andreas are German,
Teemu is Finnish, Daniel is from Canada).

@end itemize

In any case, we would @emph{really} be glad to receive your comments
about VICE.

Thanks!


@node Contributing, Newsgroups, Sending feedback, Contacts
@section How to contribute

If you want to make a major contribution, please @emph{ask} first.  It
has already happened a couple of times that somebody started working at
something that had already been done but not released to the public, and
we really do @emph{not} want anybody to waste time.

If you are going to make a patch, please make sure the patch is relative
to the very latest version, and provide us with the following:

@itemize @bullet
@item
a diff file containing all the changes you have made (@samp{diff -c} or
@samp{diff -u} (better) is fine; please don't use plain @samp{diff});
@item
GNU-style @file{ChangeLog} entries with a list of the changes you have
made (look at the @file{ChangeLog}s provided with the original VICE
sources for an example).
@end itemize

This is very important, and makes it much smoother and safer for us to
include patches.

People willing to port VICE to other platforms are always welcome.  A
Windows and a MacOS port are in the works, so if you are interested in
those platforms, please let us know.  There is plenty of work to do and
any sort of help can be very useful.


